{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_archylee_ver01/data/sn82016196/00516992438/1949012001/0048.xml":{"full_text":"-The California Eagle, Thursday, January 20, 1949\n4\nTrade Union Conference\nTo Discuss Unemployment\nKeynoter for the Trade Union\nConference called by the Inde\npendent Progressive Party will be\nWilliam Elconin, international\nrepresentative of the United\nElectrical, Radio and Machine\nWorkers, according to Erward\nMosk, Los Angeles County IPP\nchairman. Hugh Bryson, nation\nal president of the Marine Cooks\nand Stewards, and IPP state\nchairman, who had been sched\nuled to give the keynote ad\ndress, left Sunday night for\nWashington, D. C.\nMosk expects the high point\nof the conference to be the\nhammering out of the initial\nsteps in a campaign to meet\nBond Sales Growing\nUnited States Savings Bonds\nsales in Southern California\nduring December, 1948, regis\ntered a substantial increase in\nvolume over the previous\nmonth\u2019s total, according to J. B.\nMessick, director of Treasury\nbond sales for this area.\nNo species of falsehood is\nmore frequent than flattery; to\nwhich the coward is betrayed by\nfear, the dependent by interest,\nand the friend by tenderness.\n\u2014Caleb C. Colton\nIt in the EAGLE\nSay You Saw\nPILES FISTULAS FISSURES SWELLING\nRECTAL BLEEDING RECTAL ITCHING\nTREATED IN THE OFFICE\nAo Hospitalization 12 Months to Pay\nJ. T. GEORGE, M.D.\nVA. 7385\nNow Save\nii\nper gallon\nGUAHAHTetH highest\noctane CASOUNC!\nWITH THE SAME\nSVMKt SWICt!\nYOUR NEAREST\ne,A,BSTA ON\nI hUIIv VERNON\n\\Ulinlu/\nRUG CLEANING\n9x12 Rugs Cleaned as Low as S^OO\nAll Rugs Insured While In Our Care\nGOLDEN STATE RUG CLEANERS\n167? E. 32nd Street Phone ADams 6935\nBM 2 \"\"\u201ci C 'Ox\n5 47TH PLACE\ni 48 l 3 W E\nV\nNEW j pGO\nCOMMONWEALTH e\nLOAN COMPANY\nOFFICE pr\nCash in a hurry\u2014that\nIs what Cowmen* I _\nwealth's new loan ef* Cw' J\nFite offers you. No v\nneed to let unpaid RL y\u2014\nbills set you down.\nNo need to pass up a T. 12^ f\nsmart buy for lack of r 11\ncask. Decide how C7 P'r~~~-aA ft\u2019\nmuch you need. Then\nphone us or stop in\nI at the new Common- f NEW\nwealth office. When I\nyeur loan is approved, V LOAN UrrlCt y gA\nrir* NOW OPENJ K\n.Commonwealth\nLOAN COMPANY JI\n4750 S. CENTRAL PHONE: AD. 3-7241\nBusiness Established 1887\nthe unemployment crisis now\ndeveloping with increasing ra\npidity.\nIPP leaders pointing out that\naccording to Labor Department\nfigures, approximately a half\nmillion workers lost their jobs\nlast week. Reports coming in to\nProgressive Party headquarters\nfrom various unions show that\nthe membership of some unions\nis being seriously hit by lay-offs\nin consumer goods industries.\n\"Unemployment is a state\nand national problem but we\nintend to start the ball rolling\nin this area for a fighting pro\ngram that will mobilize both\nthe unions and the communi\nties and we expect the trade\nunionists to hammer out a\npractical program.\" Mosk stat\ned.\nIndividual trade unionists of\nall branches of labor, without\nregard to party affiliations, have\nbeen invited to attend the Pro\ngressive Party's conference, Sat\nurday, January 22, at Park View\nManor, 2200 W. Seventh st. The\nconference is scheduled to open\nat 10 a.m. and adjourn at 3 p.m.\nIn addition to discussing leg\nislative issues such as Taft-\nHartley repeal and the full rein\nstatement of the Wagner and\nNorris-La Guardia Acts, and the\nunemployment crisis, the confer\nence will also discuss the Pro\ngressive Party and labor\u2019s politi\ncal fight. A permanent Progres\nsive Party labor committee will\nbe set up.\nPostage Due\nNot So Great\nFanning Says\nPostmaster Michael D. Fan\nning announces that the num\nber of letters going through the\npost office with insufficient post\nage has dropped to 10,000 per\nday from a peak of 50,000 daily\nwhen the new postage rates\nwent into effect on January 1.\nRates were \u201cupped\u201d on nearly\nevery class of mail except first\nclass letters and cards. Air mail\nletters weighing up to and in\ncluding 8 ounces now require 6\ncents per ounce instead of 5\ncents, but the rate for air post\ncards hrfs been reduced to 4\ncents. All air mail rates apply\nto mail sent by air to any point\nwithin the United States and pos\nsessions, and to Canada and\nMexico.\nLet Some Air\nInto The Room\nRecent cold weather has pro\nduced a long yet needless list of\nfatalities resulting from carbon\nmonoxide asphyxiation in the\nLos Angeles area.\nIn most all cases the victims\nwere overcome in unventilated\nrooms heated by gas heaters.\nNatural gas itself is non-poison\nous, yet the carbon monoxide\nproduced in burning it is deadly.\nSafety demands the inflexible\nrule never to occupy a gas heat\ned room unless it is adequately\nventilated at all times.\nWilkins to Speak\nMILWAUKEE Roy Wilkins.\nNAACP assistant secretary, will\naddress the annual educational\nconference of the CIO United Au\ntomobile Workers here on Fri\nday. Two thousand delegates\nfrom UAW locals across the coun\ntry are \u2022expected to attend this\nconference.\nHousekeeping Rooms as Low\nas $5.00 Per Week\nat\n112 Weller Street\nW.\nDemand This\nProtection!\nBONDED\nSERVICE\nPOLICY\nA WRITTEN, ironclad service\npolicy that ASSURES\nLONGER DRIVING\nPLEASURE at no extra cost:\nOFFERED ONLY by\nWashington\nMotors\nMANY MORE LIKE THESE\n'35 PLYMOUTH COUPE\n$95\nSpecial today only (9W4291)\n\u201936 DODGE SEDAN\n$195\nReal transportation buy. (2E7452)\n'36 OLDS. COUPE\n$295\nToday\u2019s best., buy. <Mtr. P 587653)\nW 5\nOutstanding buy. (8U7424)\n\u201937 CHEV. SEDAN\n$395\nWorth the money. (7N1175)\n'39 DODGE SEDAN\n$595\nThis \u00abi a good one (64D361)\nPACK. '4l CONVERTIBLE\n$795\n\u201c6\" Extras (3X1475)\n'4l OLDS SEDAN\n$795\nTerrific value. (68E314)\nSTUDE. \u201942 CHAMP. SED.\n$945\nO'drive (ST3m)\n'47 FORD SEDAN\n$1395\nR. H. 2-dr dlx. S. (7Y315)\n\u201946 CHEV. SEDAN\n$1495\nS.M. 4-dr. (71P307)\nSTUDE. '47 CHAMP. SED.\n$1695\nDlx 4-dr. (47U176)\n\u20194B PLYMOUTH SEDAN\n$1945\nLow mi. R &H. spc 4-dr. (32Y848)\nand You'll Buy From\nBuy by Comparison\nWashington\nMotors\nCORNER OF\nWashington Figueroa\nOpen eves. A. Sun. till\n9 P.M. RI. 6293\nis the topic of discussion by this group of diligent YWCA workers. Miss Haze\nMEMBERSHIP\nA. Macbeth, (center) special campaign chairman and her captains are pictured above.\nMiss Macbeth says \u201cComing together is a beginning, Keeping together is progress and\nworking together is success.\u201d Mrs. Irene Morris, organizer and chairman of the \u201947 club\nof the Woodlawn Branch YWCA is making an appeal to all \u201947 club members to again\nlend their support in making this drive a success.\nCited for Aid\nTo 4-H Health\nDr. Roscoe C. Brown, senior\nhealth specialist of the U.S. Pub\nlic Health Service, was presented\na 4-H citation plaque recently\nfor outstanding service by the\nNation's 300.000 colored 4-H club\nboys and girls.\nPresentation was made at the\nU. S. Department of Agriculture\nby Dr. Erwin H. Shinn, field\nagent of 4-H work in the Sou\nthern States and Puerto Rico.\nThree 4-H representatives and a\nscore of agricultural officials\nwere present for the ceremony.\nIn making the presentation,\nDr. Shinn said that perhaps\nBooker T. Washington and Dr.\nBrown have done more than any\nother individuals in our country\nto promote health improvement\nconditions for rural and urban\ncolored Americans.\nHe pointed out that Booker\nWashington founded National\nNegro Health Week 35 years ago\nand that its annual observance\nhas been continued largely\nthrough the efforts of Dr. Brown\nwho has devoted the greater\npart of his life to public health\nwork.\nWomen Are People\nSANTIAGO. Chile (G)\nChilean women last week were\ngiven the right to full political\nequality with men, including the\nright to run for Congress, the\nPresidency and all other political\noffices by President Gabriel\nGonzales Videla, when he signed\ninto law such a bill.\n\u00ab\"OPRESS\u201d\n\u2022operior PRESSING\nill is extra light ana\neaxes the hair with\na beautiful glossy\nsheen,contains heat\nresisting oils that\nrelieve the hair from\nbreaking off and\ncounter. 2ac and\n56c. Vse \u201cXI GKO\nScalp Ointment Ssr\nand 50c and \"GOLD\nKIST\" Shamnoo 40c\nGolden State Toilet\nProduct*, Station K,\nBox IW. Eos An-\nteles* Calif-\nHOME CARE FOR\nSMALL CHILDREN\n2 to 8 years old. RE. 6108.\n2722 Kenwood Ave., near\nschools. ts\nWholesalers Outlet Store\nSHOE DEPARTMENT\n826 SOUTH BROADWAY, LOS ANGELES\nOPENING SPECIALS\nSHOES\nMENS Goodyear Welt s>l9s\nLeather Sole\n$7.95 Value Only\nMENS NATIONALLY KNOWN BRANDS\nValues S E9S $095\nTo $13.95 tO\n500 PAIRS LADIES GOLD CROSS SHOES\ns>l9s SE9S\nValues JIH.\nTo $11.95 \"t and\nLADIES WELL KNOWN MAKES OF\nDRESS and PLAY SHOES\nValves 515.95 $4 89 95\nOpening\nSpecials TO\nWE CARRY ALL SIZES\nBring This Ad and 1 o^4\nReceive Discount A V /0\nON ANY SHOE PURCHASED DURING THIS\nJANUARY OPENING SALE\nSeek Youths\nFra Holdup\nAnd Shooting\nNewton police are hot on the\ntrial of two young hoodlums, one\nof whom has a nervous trigger\nfinger, for an attempted hold-up\nland a serious assault with a\n\u2019deadly weapon.\nThe cause of the police hunt is\nithe serious Injury of Mrs. Fannie\nDouglas, who conducts a grocery\nstore with her husband at 2800\nGriffith. Mrs. Douglas was shot\nin the left hand Saturday night\nwhen she was alone in the store.\nAccording to her version of the\nstory, one of the youths entered\nthe store about seven fifteen and\npurchased some candy. A few\nminutes later he returned and\nasked for a can of soup. Mrs.\nDouglas who was behind the\ncounter, told him to get the soup\nwhich was on a shelf on the\nother side of the store. He said\nhe would go out and see if his\nbuddy wanted soup.\nHe left.and returned with an\nother young, man who stood in\nthe door. The first youth, about\n18 then asked him if he wanted\nsoup. The newcomer replied in\nthe negative.\nThe first youth, acting queerly,\nwalked toward the end of the\ncounter, then turned as though\nto leave the store. He wheeled\nsuddenly with a gun in his hand\nand announced to Mrs. Douglas,\n\u201cThis is a stick-up.\nMrs. Douglas evidently did\nnot frighten sufficiently, for the\nhoodlum with the gun became\nnervous and in his trembling ex\ncitement, he discharged the gun.\nThe bullet lodged between the\nthumb and forfinger of Mrs.\nDouglas\u2019 left hand. She was\ntaken to Angelus hospital.\nThe hold-up duo is not known\nin the community and they arc\nthought to be two of three youths\nwho were loitering in front of\nthe store Friday night. Police\nhave a good description of them\nand an arrest is expected this\nweek.\nMonday morning the revolver\nused in the shooting was found\nin the yard behind the store.\nEmory Douglas, husband of the\ninjured woman said he would\nhave a watchman on the\npremises from now on since this\nis the second robbery attempt in\ntwo years.\nDimes Provide\nTuskegee With\nPolio Defense\nTUSKEGEE INSTITUTE, Ala.\u2014\nPolio patients at the Tuskegee\nI Polio Center enjoy the best care\n\u25a0and treatment money can pro\nvide. Appropriations totaling Sl,-\nj 486,660 have been made to Tus\nikegee Institute by the National\n(Foundation for Infantile Paraly\nlsis from*funds raised in the an\n(nual March^of Dimes.\nI Highly trained personnel, ex\ncellent facilities and equipment,\nand support of allied research\n(and health training programs\n(afford polio patients at Tuskegee\n(the most advanced care and\n(treatment.\nIt is only through public sup\nport of the March of Dimes,\nwhich is now under way, that\nthe 'National Foundation can\ncarry on its work.\nA Big Headache for\nThe Guys Who Pay If\nUncle Sam embarked upon\nhis biggest \u201cpaper\u201d job of the\nentire year this week\u2014the task\n(of gathering income tax returns\nfrom all citizens and residents\nof the United States. In these\ndays, that includes most of us.\nThe Bureau of Internal Rev\nenue estimates that between to\nday and March 15, which is the\nfinal date for the filing of in\ndividual returns, 50,000,000 re\nturns will be filed throughout\n(the United States.\nDiphtheria\nHits All Ages\nAn 81-year-old man is Los An\ngeles\u2019 first diphtheria case for\n1949, Dr. George M. Uhl, city\nhealth officer, said this week.\nHe is John Hylin, 237 S. Flow\ner st., who was reported to be\nin serious condition at Los An\ngelos County General Hospital.\nThe case also brought another\nwarning from Dr. Uhl for parents\nof children between the ages of\n6 months and 11 years, who are\ncurrently being immunized by\nprivate physicians, schools, and\n(health department clinics.\nNew Short Form\nHarry C. Westover, Collector of\nInternal Revenue for Southern\nCalifornia, today called atten\ntion of taxpayers to the new in\ncome tax form which will be\nused by many taxpayers this\nyear. It is the new Form 1040-A,\nwhich may be filed by most wage\nearners with incomes of less than\n55,000.00 who want the Collector\nto compute their tax.\nNo More Needed\nThe Department of Employ\nment reports that there is ade\nquate farm labor in all areas\nof the state, with labor surpluses\ndeveloping in some parts of the\nstate. Edward F. Hayes, Chief\nof Farm Placement for the De\npartment, said the continued\ncold wave has been the prin\ncipal cause for the loss of em\nployment by many agricultural\nworkers.\n1949 Prospects\nA panel, featuring local au\nthorities, will be the sounding\nboard for airing of opinions on\n1949 prospects at a Los Angeles\nChamber of Commerce business\noutlook conference at the Am\nbassador hotel next Thursday,\naccording to Chairman Paul S.\nArmstrong.\nMarried women who apply for\nchange of name on their Social\nSecurity cards will receive more\nrapid service if they submit their\nold card with their application.\nThe number remains the same.\nSouthwest Realty Hoard\nPolicy on Restrictions\nThe following is the Race Restrictions Policy adopted\nunanimously by a vote of the membership, June 30, 1947.\n\u201cTo abide by the Code of Ethics of the Na\ntional Association of Real Estate Boards, as\nset forth in Part 3, Article 34, of \u2019Relating\nto Customers and the Public, which is as\nfollows:\n\u2018A Realtor should never be instsumental in\nintroducing into a neighborhood a char\nacter of property, or occupancy, members\nof any race or nationality, or any other\nindividuals whose presence will clearly\nbe detrimental to property values in that\nneighborhood.\u2019\nResponsibility, in the event of a violation, will rest\nentirely with the Realtor member making or cooperating\nWhen making a deal in a doubtful area. Broker shall\nuse diligence and caution before accepting a deposit, where\ncriticism or complaints may follow.\n(Check district for possible legal action pending, or\nunder way, for the protection of property values in the\narea; see if any re-restriction program is under way. or\nprotests entered against violations.)\nCheck with at least 2 Board Member Brokers in the\narea where sale is to be made who are located nearest the\nproperty for their opinion as to whether the deal would be\nin violation of Article 34. If you are in doubt about where\nthe members are, the Board will furnish such names upon\nRetain their names, and information with the date, for\nreference in vour file; in the event of complaint, it will\nestablish the\u2018fact of your chocking the district.\nUse every precaution to maintain a good name for the\nSouthwest Branch, as well as your own office. A commission\nearned that invites a lawsuit, arbitration, or endangers your\nreputation, or membership in the Southwest Branch, is\nmoney that you can well afford to pass up.\nThis policy now places the responsibility on the indi\nvidual Broker and his office that makes the deal.\u201d\nRally for Civil Rights\nCalled in Washington. D. C.\nFor February 11 and 12\nOne hundred leading Amer-1\n(lean leading American citizens\n(issued a call today to a Legisla\ntive Assembly and Rally for\n(Civil Rights February 11-12 in\nthe nation\u2019s capital \u201cas a demon\nstration of the united will of\nAmericans to bring to an end\nnow the practices of discrimina\ntion and segregation.\u201d\nThe call was announced hy\nDr. J. Finley Wilson, Grand Ex\nalted Ruler of the Improved\nBenevolent and Protective Order,:\nof Elks of the World, a sponsor\n(of the conference. Initiating!\n(sponsors joining with Dr. Wilson\n(include Dr. W. E. B. Du\u00dfois, of\nthe Council on African Affairs.\nI NYC; Dr. Benjamin F. Mays,\nPresident of Morehouse College,\nAtlanta. Ga.\nDr. William H. Jernagin, Presi\ndent of the National Baptist Sun\nday School and BTU Congress,\nWashington, D. C.; Bishop D.\nWard Nichols of the African\nMethodist Episcopa 1 Church,\nNYC; John Wesley Dobbs, Grand;\n(Master of the Prince Hall Lodge,!\nF&A Masons, Atlanta, Ga.: and I\nDr. William H. Borders. Pastor\nof the Wheat St. Baptist Church,;\nAtlanta, Ga.\nDeclaring that \"a determined\nand powerful minority of Con\ngressmen has blocked civil\nrights legislation year after\nyear,\u201d the call asserts that\n\"the time has come to end\n4once and for all the denial to\nour own citizens of the rights\nwe proclaim throughout the\nworld.\nThe right of every American\ncitizen to equal protection of the\nlaws regardless of race or color\nhas been systematically denied\nin practice to millions of Negro\ncitizens. Segregation is their lot\nfrom birth to death.\u201d\nLincoln's Birthday\nPlans for the Lincoln Birthday\nweekend meeting call for dele\ngations to visit Congressional\nleaders, heads of Executive De\npartments and civil organiza\ntions in the District of Columbia,\nand to demand action on civil\nrights bills.\nOne purpose of the assembly\nand rally, according to the Call,\nwill be to \u2018\u2018insistently call for\nan end to the flagrant segrega\ntion practices in the nation\u2019s\ncapital which are a. living re\nbuke to our professions of de\nmocracy.\u201d\nThe principal legislation the\nLegislative Assembly will be\nconcerned with includes the\nFair Employment Practices\nBill, the Anti-Poll Tax Bill, the\nAnti-Lynch Bill, Federal Aid to\nEducation, and measures to\nwipe out discrimination in\nFederal employment and in\nthe District of Columbia.\nThe meetings of the Legisla\ntive Assembly will take place at\nthe Metropolitan. Avenue Baptist\nChurch, 1225 R Street, N.W. Fri\nday and Saturday, February 11\nand 12. A Civil Rights rally will\nbe held Friday night at the\nchurch. Speakers will be an\nnounced.\nAmong the co-sponsors are:\nRev. Wade C. Banclay, Metho\ndist Board of Foreign Missions,\nNYC; Elmer A. Benson, Chair\nman, Progressive Party, Apple\nton, Minnesota; Mary McLeod\nBethune, President, National\nCouncil of Negro Women, Wash\nington, D. C.; Dr. Clark W. Cum\nmings, Executive Secretary Fed\neration of Churches, St. Louis,\nMissouri; Charlotta A. Bass, Los\nAngeles.\nClarence Derwent, President,\nActors Equity, NYC; Dr. Charles\nDrew, Howard University Medi\ncal School, Washington, D. C.;\nI Prof. Thomas Emerson, Yate Law\nSchool, New Haven, Conn.; Rev.\nProf. J. Fletcher, Episcopal Theo\nlogical Seminary, Cambridge\nMass.; and Dr. Clark Foreman,\nWashington, D. C.\nFollowing are additional co\nsponsors: Lester Granger, Co-ex\necutive Secretary National Urban\nLeague, New York City; George\nHarper, Executive Secretary, Na\ntional Council of Methodist\nYouth, Nashville, Tennessee.\nPerry W. Howard, National Re\npublican Committeeman, Missis\nsippi; W. C. Hueston, Commis\nsioner of Education, 1.8.P.0.E. of\nW., Washington, \u2022D. C.; Dr.\nAlphaeus Hunton, Executive Di\nrector, Council on African Af\nfairs, NYC; Dr. D. V. Jemison,\nPresident. National Baptist Con\nvention, Selma, Alabama.\nDr. David D. Jones, Bennett\nCollege, Greensboro, N. C.; Rev.\nWilliam E. Lampe, General Sec\nretary, Evangelical Reformed\nChurch, Philadelphia, Pa.; Carle\nton L. Lee, Dean of the Chapel,\nTuskegee Institute, Tuskegee,\nAlabama; Carey McWilliams.\nLos Angeles, California; Dmitri\nMitropoulous, NYC.\nEstelle M. Osborne, NYC; Jen\nnings Perry, Nashville, Tenn.;\nRev. C. T. Pratt, Bishop, Church\nof God In Union Assembly, Dal\nton, Ga.; Magistrate Hobson R.\nReynolds, Philadelphia, Pa.;\nHazel Scott, NYC.\nRev. Guy Emery Shipler, Edi\ntor, Churchman, NYC; Dr. Wen\ndell C. Somerville, Executive Sec\nretary, Lott Carey Baptist For\neign Mission Convention, Wash\nington, D. *C.; Mrs. Leslie E.\nSwain, President, Women's Am\nerican Baptist Foreign Mission\nary Society, Craigville, Massa\nchusetts; Henry A. Wallace,\nSouh Salem, N. Y.; and James\nWaterman Wise, Director, Coun\ncil Against Intolerance, NYC.\nSojourner Home\nPlans Program\nPlans have been completed for\nthe very brilliant affair to be\nheld at the Sojourner Truth\nHome, 1119 East Adams Blvd.,\nSunday, January 23rd, from five\nthirty to six-thirty. Mrs. Emma\nSurrey and her committee of the\n\"Willing Workers\u201d have done a\ndynamic job in attempting to\nmake this an outstanding affair.\nTwo fine artists will be the\nfeature of the evening and the\nentire series will be done by\ncandlelight. A light buffet sup\nper will follow the program.\nThe affair is a benefit one as\nthe group will use all resources\nto pay for some little necessities\nthat will lend beauty to the\nhome. Any member of the home\nis eligible to join this group. The\npublic is invited.\nMonday, January 24 from two\nto four will be the regular edu\ncational day at the home. Mrs.\nMartha Tate Dodge and Mrs.\nWilma Chapman have secured\nProfessor Hoffman as the guest\nspeaker and Mr. and Mrs. Page\nof New York will furnish the\nmusic. Mrs. Hailstock will have\ncharge of the social hour.\nLabor Ad Change\nSeveral far-reaching changes\nin the Fair Labor Standards Act\n(Federal wage and hour law)\nare recommended in the annua!\nreport of William R. McComb\nAdministrator of the Wage and\nHour and Public Contracts Divi\nsions, which was submitted to\nthe 81st Congress on Monday.","height":"30548","width":"21992"}}
